[visit] The useful information from visiting https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boris_Rauschenbach for user goal 'Check if Boris Rauschenbach is a military flight engineer' as follows: 

Evidence in page: 
Boris Viktorovich Rauschenbach ... Russian physicist of German ethnicity who worked as an engineer in the former Soviet space program.
Trained as an engineer, he found great success in designing rockets and who developed the theory and instruments for interplanetary flight control and navigation in 1955-1960s.
The only aviation-related college in Leningrad was a newly established Institute of Civil Air Fleet, later converted into a military academy. After a brief work at an aircraft plant, Rauschenbach completed his studies at this Institute (1932-1937)
Sergey Korolyov assigned Rauschenbach to flight control automation for his winged rocket (cruise missile) project. ... Until 1941, Rauschenbach worked on jet combustion stability, a program that resulted in effective and stable Rocket artillery projectiles.
Rauschenbach's first major success was the lunar flyby of Luna 3 in October 1959, that returned the first photographs of Moon's far side. This was followed by flight control systems for interplanetary probes to Venus, Mars and crewed orbital space flight. ... Rauschenbach also designed instruments for the Vostok 3-Vostok 6 joint flight and the first Soyuz spacecraft docking systems.

Summary: 
Boris Rauschenbach was not exactly a 'military flight engineer.' He was a physicist and aerospace engineer who primarily worked in the Soviet space program. While he did study at the Institute of Civil Air Fleet (which later became a military academy) and worked on military-related projects such as cruise missiles and rocket artillery early in his career, his major contributions and professional recognition stem from his work designing rockets, flight control automation, and navigation systems for spacecraft and interplanetary probes.
