Krafft Arnold Ehricke (March 24, 1917 – December 11, 1984) was a German rocket-propulsion engineer and advocate for space colonization. Ehricke is a co-designer of the first Centaur liquid oxygen/liquid hydrogen upper stage.
Born in Berlin, Ehricke believed in the feasibility of space travel from a very young age... He attended the Technische Hochschule in Berlin... and studied celestial mechanics and nuclear physics... attaining his degree in Aeronautical Engineering.
He worked at Peenemünde as a propulsion engineer from 1942 to 1945... then went to the United States with other German rocket scientists and technicians under "Operation Paperclip" in 1947.
While at Convair, he designed the D-1 Centaur, the world's first upper-stage-booster that used liquid hydrogen and oxygen. He also created an early space station design... The NEXUS reusable rocket was a 1960s concept designed by a group at General Dynamics led by Ehricke.
Ehricke was well-known in the field of astrodynamics and its applications... Although he was not the first, he clearly demonstrated the so-called "gravity assist" method for utilizing hyperbolic encounters with an intermediate planet to increase (or decrease) the velocity and orbital elements of a space vehicle.
Ehricke promoted a philosophical concept called the "Extraterrestrial Imperative." This idea refers to Ehricke's belief that it was the responsibility of humanity to explore space and exploit the resources of the Solar System, in order to sustain the development of the species.
