Born 30 June 1914 Siedlce, Lublin Governorate, Russian Empire (now Poland). Died 8 December 1984 (aged 70)[1] Moscow, Russian SFSR, Soviet Union. Resting place Novodevichy Cemetery, Moscow. Alma mater National Academy of Sciences of Ukraine. Known for Creation of the first Soviet pulse jet engine, development of Proton rockets and UR-100, UR-200, UR-500 and UR-700 ICBMs. Awards Twice Hero of Socialist Labour. Fields Rocket engineering. Institutions Kyiv Polytechnic Institute Institute of Mathematics of the National Academy of Sciences of Ukraine National Aviation University Baranov Central Institute of Aviation Motor Development.

Vladimir Nikolayevich Chelomey or Chelomei ... 30 June 1914 – 8 December 1984) was a Soviet engineer and designer in the missile program of the former Soviet Union. He invented the first Soviet pulse jet engine and was responsible for developing the world's first anti-ship cruise missiles and the ICBM program of the Soviet Union such as the UR-100, UR-200, UR-500 and UR-700.

Summary: 
Vladimir Chelomey (born June 30, 1914, in Siedlce, Russian Empire; died December 8, 1984, in Moscow) was a prominent Soviet engineer and designer specializing in rocket engineering. He is best known for creating the first Soviet pulse jet engine, developing the world's first anti-ship cruise missiles, and spearheading the Soviet ICBM program with the UR-100, UR-200, UR-500 (Proton rocket), and UR-700. He was affiliated with institutions like the Kyiv Polytechnic Institute and the Baranov Central Institute of Aviation Motor Development, and was awarded the title Hero of Socialist Labour twice.
